  "statement": {
    "ambiguity_status": "minor",
    "intended": "Let $f$ be a Rademacher multiplicative function: a random $\\{-1,0,1\\}$-valued multiplicative function, where for each prime $p$ we independently choose $f(p)\\in \\{-1,1\\}$ uniformly at random, and for square-free integers $n$ we extend $f(p_1\\cdots p_r)=f(p_1)\\cdots f(p_r)$ (and $f(n)=0$ if $n$ is not squarefree). Does there exist some constant $c>0$ such that, almost surely,\\[\\limsup_{N\\to \\infty}\\frac{\\sum_{m\\leq N}f(m)}{\\sqrt{N\\log\\log N}}=c?\\]",
